data.name: Label3.Text
data.value: The ‘Minimum price bars between turns’ is a way of finding major or minor retraces and extensions. A number of 3, for example, will find small peaks and valleys. A value of 10 will find peaks at least 10 price bars from one another. Valleys will also be no closer than 10 bars apart.

data.name: Label1.Text
data.value: Most controls are self-explanatory. Symbol: Add a stock symbol from your portfolio, not selected on the prior form, for which you want to find an extension or retrace. ‘All Portfolios’ button tells the program to use data from all portfolios. Once data appears in the grid (D), clicking on a row draws the associated chart (E). On the chart, three red circles mark the three turns in the retrace or extension.

data.name: Label4.Text
data.value: Select the retrace or extension at A. Doing so ungrays Start button (C). ‘All’ check boxes means the program will find any extension or retrace within the selected dates (B). Plus/minus ( +/- ) is the window width for the retrace or extension calculation. For example, if 38% extension is checked and +/- shows 2, then the program will find all extensions in the range of 36% to 40%.
